label.value: delayed onset of homologous chromosome pairing at cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome pairing during meiosis (synapsis) is delayed at a cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region such as the sme2 locus.

label.value: Mei2 nuclear dot absent from cell

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the cell does not contain a detectable Mei2 nuclear dot complex.

definition.value: In some mutants, a focus that contains meiRNA but not Mei2 can form; this is called the meiRNA nuclear dot.

label.value: abnormal RNA localization

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of an RNA in a cell is abnormal. An RNA may be observed in a place where it is not normally found, absent from a place where it is normally found, or both.

label.value: normal RNA localization

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of an RNA in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal RNA localization to chromatin

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of an RNA to chromatin is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased meiotic recombination at cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of reciprocal meiotic recombination at a cis-acting homologous chromosome pairing region such as the sme2 locus is decreased.

label.value: meiotic cell cycle in zygote with unfused nuclei

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the two nuclei in a zygote formed by conjugation with cellular fusion undergo meiosis before karyogamy with nuclear fusion is completed.

label.value: abnormal nuclear congression during mating

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which nuclear migration involved in conjugation with cellular fusion is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal cytoskeleton morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal cytoskeleton morphology.

label.value: abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the microtubule cytoskeleton is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology.

label.value: abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology during mating

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the microtubule cytoskeleton is abnormal during conjugation with cellular fusion.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton morphology.

label.value: abnormal sporulation resulting in formation of ascus with fewer than four spores

value.value: A sporulation phenotype in which asci that contain one, two, or three spores form following conjugation and subsequent sporulation.

label.value: abnormal replication fork reversal

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which stalled replication forks are unwound four-stranded structures resembling Holliday junctions, but are not subsequently resolved correctly.

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at replication forks during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at replication forks is decreased during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to chromatin at replication forks during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at replication forks is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal single-stranded DNA 5'-3' exodeoxyribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a single-stranded DNA 5'-3' exodeoxyribonuclease activity is abnormal.

label.value: abolished single-stranded DNA 5'-3' exodeoxyribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which a single-stranded DNA 5'-3' exodeoxyribonuclease activity is absent.

label.value: abnormal primary amine oxidase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of primary amine oxidase activity is abnormal.

label.value: decreased primary amine oxidase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of primary amine oxidase activity is decreased.

label.value: abolished protein localization to pericentric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to pericentric heterochromatin is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein kinase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal protein autophosphorylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the autophosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Protein autophosphorylation is the phosphorylation by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues, or residues on an identical protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein autophosphorylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of autophosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein autophosphorylation during cellular response to DNA damage

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the autophosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur during a cellular response to DNA damage. Protein autophosphorylation is the phosphorylation by a protein of one or more of its own amino acid residues, or residues on an identical protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal genetic imprinting at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which genetic imprinting at the mating-type locus is abnormal.

label.value: abolished genetic imprinting at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which genetic imprinting at the mating-type locus does not occur.

label.value: decreased genetic imprinting at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which genetic imprinting at the mating-type locus occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: normal genetic imprinting at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which genetic imprinting at the mating-type locus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal replication fork arrest at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest at the mating-type locus is abnormal.

label.value: abolished replication fork arrest at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest at the mating-type locus does not occur.

label.value: decreased replication fork arrest at mating-type locus

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest at the mating-type locus occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: normal chromatin binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal chromatin binding at mating-type region replication fork barrier

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) at a replication fork barrier in the mating-type region.

label.value: abnormal replication fork arrest

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal replication fork arrest at rDNA repeats

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest at sites within the eukaryotic rDNA repeat spacer is abnormal.

label.value: decreased replication fork arrest at rDNA repeats

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which replication fork arrest at abnormal replication fork arrest at sites within the eukaryotic rDNA repeat spacer occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: decreased chromatin binding at rDNA replication fork barrier

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) at a replication fork pausing site within the eukaryotic rDNA repeat spacer in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene, and may normally bind DNA, protein, or both in chromatin.

label.value: decreased chromatin binding at mating-type region replication fork barrier

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of chromatin binding by a gene product (usually a protein) at a replication fork pausing site within the mating-type region in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene, and may normally bind DNA, protein, or both in chromatin.

label.value: increased Argonaute-associated RNA length

value.value: A phenotype in which small RNA molecules physically associated with the Argonaute protein (Ago1) are longer than normal.

label.value: decreased centromeric outer repeat transcript level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which RNAs transcribed from the centromere outer repeat region are present at lower levels than normal.

definition.value: This term encompasses both unprocessed RNA transcribed from the centromere outer repeat region and siRNAs derived by dicer-mediated processing of the primary transcripts. Use this term only for levels of RNA transcribed from endogenous centromere outer repeat sequences. For levels of RNA transcribed from an exogenous reporter gene placed in the outer repeat region, consider 'abnormal chromatin silencing at centromere outer repeat region' (FYPO:0002346).

label.value: viable elongated vegetative cell, with progressive elongation

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is viable and elongated, and continues to become longer over successive generations. The cell also undergoes mitosis beginning when the cell is longer than normal.

definition.value: Note that progressive cell elongation usually results from DNA damage checkpoint activation. Consider also annotating to 'normal DNA damage checkpoint' (FYPO:0001705) or 'increased DNA damage checkpoint activation' (FYPO:0001707).

label.value: decreased histone H3-K9 methylation at centromere outer repeat during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which methylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in centromere outer repeat regions occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: abolished histone H3-K9 methylation at centromere outer repeat during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which methylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in centromere outer repeat regions does not occur.

label.value: abnormal heterochromatin assembly at centromere outer repeat during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which heterochromatin assembly is abnormal in centromere outer repeat regions. Heterochromatin assembly is the assembly of chromatin into a compact and highly condensed form that is often, but not always, transcriptionally silent.

label.value: normal heterochromatin assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which heterochromatin assembly is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Heterochromatin assembly is the assembly of chromatin into a compact and highly condensed form that is often, but not always, transcriptionally silent.

label.value: normal heterochromatin assembly at protein coding gene

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which heterochromatin assembly is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in regions containing protein-coding genes. Heterochromatin assembly is the assembly of chromatin into a compact and highly condensed form that is often, but not always, transcriptionally silent.

label.value: decreased heterochromatin assembly at protein coding gene

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which heterochromatin assembly occurs to a lower extent than normal in regions containing protein-coding genes. Heterochromatin assembly is the assembly of chromatin into a compact and highly condensed form that is often, but not always, transcriptionally silent.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 methylation at protein coding gene during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which methylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in regions containing protein-coding genes occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased mRNA-derived small RNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of small RNA (such as siRNA) derived from mRNA transcripts measured in a cell is lower than normal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased mRNA-derived small RNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of small RNA (such as siRNA) derived from mRNA transcripts measured in a cell is greater than normal.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
